What are functions?
Similar to functions f(x) in math:
you can give it some x, and it will give you some f(x) back
Like a magic box that does stuff for you
Dont reinvent the wheel
You must call the function for it to work
Pass the function a argument: the x value in f(x)
Some functions return things to you: the resulting f(x) value
Function Call Syntax
functionName ( arguments )
You have collected data. Now,
you want to know the mean,
median, min, max of your data
Ex: function called mean()
Syntax
function_name(arguments)
mean( c(1,2,3,4) )
When run, returns 2.5
what I gave to the function, mean() takes a vector
what the function gives back to me

Ex: function called summary()
Syntax
function_name(arguments)
Get all the previous information with just one function!
summary( c(1,2,3,4) )
When run, prints out:
Min. 1st Qu. Median Mean 3rd Qu. Max.
1.00 1.75 2.50 2.50 3.25 4.00
Review: Functions So Far
mean(c(1,2,3,4))
median(c(1,2,3,4))
min(c(1,2,3,4))
max(c(1,2,3,4))
summary(c(1,2,3,4))
Terminology Review
summary( c(1,2,3,4) )
When run, prints out:
Min. 1st Qu. Median Mean 3rd Qu. Max.
1.00 1.75 2.50 2.50 3.25 4.00
what I gave to the function = argument
what the function gives back to me = return value/output
#Function call
Functions and Variables
numbers <- c(1,2,3,4)
mean <- mean(numbers)
median <- median(numbers)
min <- min(numbers)
max <- max(numbers)
summary <- summary(numbers)

Why use Functions?
Save time!
Does stuff for you
Organize code/clarity
mean( c(1,2,3,4) ) VS (1 + 2 + 3 + 4) / 4
First option makes it more clear you are
calculating mean
There are probably
hundreds of thousands of R
functions, if not more
start memorizing them now?
No!
R Documentation
https://www.rdocumentation.org/
Explains what each function does
What arguments it takes
Sometimes also provides an example
R Documentation: mean()
More Resources
help() and ? will also bring up documentation
help(mean)
?mean
Google is our friend!
Other Functions
nrow(_matrix here_)
Number of rows in a matrix
ncol(_matrix here_)
Number of columns in a matrix
Your Turn: sleep dataset summary
- sleep can be considered a matrix
- How many rows (students) are in the sleep dataset? Store
this value in variable num_students
- How many columns are there? Store this in variable
num_variables
Syntax Hint:
nrow(_matrix here_)
ncol(_matrix here_)
Sleep nrow, ncol
num_students <- nrow(sleep)
num_variables <- ncol(sleep)
Hard-coding is BAD
There are 20 students in the dataset, so both give
the correct mean value
Strive to make your code work even if data
changes (collect more data, exclude
samples)
Programmers are lazy! We want to reuse as
much code as possible
Other functions
print()
Youve seen this before!
Prints argument to console
Stops at ~250 rows of information
View() view all data in a new tab
sum() sums up values in vector
sqrt(), exp(), log(), abs()
sin() , cos() , tan() trigonometry
